{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3dd9fb74-c1e8-4935-a4e4-23705b664a57","content":"Yes, both are known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Here's the breakdown:\n\n---\n\n**1. Tests lose history in Azure DevOps**\n\nMSTest v4 changed the default **test-ID algorithm**. Azure DevOps keys history on that ID, so every test looks new. Fix it by opting back into the legacy ID scheme in your csproj:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <TestIdGenerationStrategy>Legacy</TestIdGenerationStrategy>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\nOr, accept the new IDs and let history start fresh (recommended long-term).\n\n---\n\n**2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]` throws**\n\nIn v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is a **class-level context** — no test is running yet, so `TestName` is not available and throws. In v3 it accidentally returned the first test's name, which was a bug.\n\nYour `SetupTests.cs` hits this directly on line 13. Fix by removing the `TestName` access in class init:\n\n```csharp\n[ClassInitialize]\npublic static void ClassInit(TestContext context)\n{\n    // context.TestName is not available here in v4\n    // Use context.FullyQualifiedTestClassName if you need the class name\n}\n```\n\nIf you need per-test setup that uses `TestName`, move that logic to `[TestInitialize]`.\n\n---\n\n**3. Other v4 changes to watch for:**\n\n| Area | Change |\n|---|---|\n| **`[DataRow]` / `[DynamicData]`** | Display names may change; affects test filtering in CI |\n| **Parallel execution** | Now enabled by default at **method** level; tests that relied on sequential execution may break. Disable with `[assembly: Parallelize(Scope = ExecutionScope.ClassLevel)]` or `DoNotParallelize` |\n| **`Assert.AreEqual` on doubles** | Tolerance comparison tightened; borderline floating-point asserts may now fail |\n| **`DeploymentItem`** | Behavior changed; test working directory may differ |\n| **`TestContext.Properties`** | Partially deprecated; some properties removed |\n| **Timeout defaults** | `[Timeout]` now uses `CooperativeCancellation` by default — tests must check `CancellationToken` to honor it |\n\nIf you want, I can apply the fix to your `SetupTests.cs` and/or add the legacy ID setting to your csproj.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"199b172c-7dbc-4a58-9ba7-11c58d19892d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user has two specific issues and is asking about MSTest v4 migration. Let me address both issues and provide additional guidance.\n\n1. **Tests appearing as brand new in Azure DevOps** - In MSTest v4, the default test ID generation changed. MSTest v3 used a legacy test ID scheme, while v4 uses a new scheme by default. This causes Azure DevOps to see them as new tests with no history.\n\n2. **TestContext.TestName in [ClassInitialize] throwing** - In MSTest v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is a class-level context, not tied to any specific test. Accessing `TestName` on it throws because there's no test running yet at class initialization time. In v3, this would return the name of the first test method, which was technically incorrect but happened to work.\n\n\nI should walk through the other breaking changes and migration strategies to give them a complete picture of what's changed between versions.","outputTokens":822,"requestId":"7C19:97105:177F023:1AE54FB:69F95FB6"},"id":"9c674d19-bae1-4308-9a87-47dd1a158e93","timestamp":"2026-05-05T03:11:04.862Z","parentId":"c266f1e2-3c9f-42af-a167-2b4746313616"}
